  "prompt": "How does AR factoring affect the balance sheet?",
  "response": "AR (Accounts Receivable) factoring affects the balance sheet in several key ways:\n\n1. Asset Composition\n- Reduces Accounts Receivable balance\n- Increases Cash balance\n- Can slightly reduce total asset value depending on factoring fees\n\n2. Cash Flow Impact\n- Provides immediate cash instead of waiting for customer payments\n- Converts accounts receivable into liquid assets\n\n3. Liability Considerations\n- May create a short-term liability if factoring is structured as a loan\n- Potentially reduces overall debt if used as a financing method\n\n4. Balance Sheet Presentation\n- Decreases accounts receivable\n- Increases cash or creates a factoring liability\n- Can improve liquidity ratios\n\n5. Financial Ratios\n- May improve accounts receivable turnover\n- Can enhance working capital\n- Potentially improves debt-to-equity ratio\n\n6. Potential Accounting Treatment\n- Depends on whether factoring is considered a sale or secured borrowing\n- Can impact financial statement classification\n\nThe specific balance sheet effect depends on the factoring agreement's structure and accounting treatment, but generally provides more immediate liquidity by converting receivables to cash.",
